61
00:05:32,400 --> 00:05:37,400
What do you think was the problem during the 2020 election?

62
00:05:37,400 --> 00:05:42,400
I was asked what in the world is the Python Software Foundation.

63
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:46,400
As a director for six years, I have been saying the same thing over and over,

64
00:05:46,400 --> 00:05:53,400
which is we are here to help build an inclusive and diverse community that is as inclusive and diverse as our users.

65
00:05:53,400 --> 00:06:00,400
I think one of the things that started some of this conversation that led to the creation of the diversity and inclusion workgroup

66
00:06:00,400 --> 00:06:04,400
was us thinking a little bit about the mandate of the Python Software Foundation.

67
00:06:04,400 --> 00:06:08,400
Again, the Python Software Foundation, we help put this event on.

68
00:06:08,400 --> 00:06:10,400
We help think about fundraising.

69
00:06:10,400 --> 00:06:15,400
We help thinking about what are the issues around the world that Pythonistas are facing.

70
00:06:15,400 --> 00:06:18,400
We own the trademark, et cetera, et cetera.

71
00:06:18,400 --> 00:06:28,400
So considering that the board of directors, unfortunately, has historically had a bias towards people in the United States or North America and Europe,

72
00:06:28,400 --> 00:06:33,400
what I think we're seeing is as we continue to grow and have a more global population of Pythonistas,

73
00:06:33,400 --> 00:06:42,400
we're not maybe reaching the plethora of issues that we could otherwise be if we were having directors

74
00:06:42,400 --> 00:06:47,400
or having more inclusion with voting members, et cetera, of Pythonistas around the world.

75
00:06:47,400 --> 00:06:52,400
One of the things I think was really great with the end of the lightning talks is we see this growth of the regional conferences,

76
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:57,400
but again, we're continuing to kind of have a little bit of a stagnant issue with outreach.

77
00:06:57,400 --> 00:07:04,400
And not to say that directors who come from the United States or directors who come from Europe don't understand these issues,

78
00:07:04,400 --> 00:07:12,400
but we all know that the people that are in these given communities are best able to speak to things that are the unique challenges in their neck of the woods.

79
00:07:12,400 --> 00:07:15,400
So I think that was one of the main things that led to this discussion.

80
00:07:15,400 --> 00:07:17,400
Again, all of us are volunteers.

81
00:07:17,400 --> 00:07:24,400
We're all very passionate about this community, but literally our mandate says we are building a diverse and inclusive environment

82
00:07:25,400 --> 00:07:28,400
and community that reflects our user population.

83
00:07:28,400 --> 00:07:30,400
So I think that was like a really big thing that kind of jumped in.

84
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:39,400
And that was something very glaring to us in the election was just seeing that we weren't maybe reaching people in a way that we could otherwise be reaching them.

85
00:07:39,400 --> 00:07:41,400
Right. That's true.

86
00:07:41,400 --> 00:07:45,400
