90
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:11,400
So I guess the membership of the PSF has expanded and also geographically and in other aspects is a lot more diverse.

91
00:08:11,400 --> 00:08:17,400
And in terms of the board nominees, at least, I think there's a lot more diversity in the nominees.

92
00:08:17,400 --> 00:08:26,400
I think what we need to look at going forward is how do we make sure that we advertise that more and continue to try and recruit members into the PSF.

93
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:33,400
Well, we do see also that there's actually more still mainly the core developers from the US.

94
00:08:33,400 --> 00:08:41,400
Does that mean that the experts are actually in the US only?

95
00:08:41,400 --> 00:08:51,400
So, I mean, there's definitely a lot of skills in the US and that's kind of obvious.

96
00:08:51,400 --> 00:08:57,400
But it's not exclusive to the US and there are definitely people with talents and skills elsewhere.

97
00:08:57,400 --> 00:09:05,400
I think before we look at addressing this and trying to make it more diverse, we need to appreciate a couple of things.

98
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:13,400
One, the healthy discussion and community of core developers is critical to the success of Python.

99
00:09:13,400 --> 00:09:17,400
And we need to protect that.

100
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:22,400
That doesn't mean that bringing new people in is going to make that worse.

101
00:09:22,400 --> 00:09:26,400
And I think we just need to kind of plan things a bit further ahead.

102
00:09:26,400 --> 00:09:32,400
Also, if you look at the poor requests to see Python, they are diverse.

103
00:09:32,400 --> 00:09:38,400
So there's people from all over the world making their first changes to see Python, submitting poor requests and things like that.

104
00:09:38,400 --> 00:09:43,400
But at the moment, you know, it's still a bit of who you know.

105
00:09:43,400 --> 00:09:52,400
And it's easier to get a poor request merged if you know some of the core developers or you're already a part of the community or you're a known person.

106
00:09:52,400 --> 00:09:57,400
So I think if we want to get more core developers from diverse geographically,

107
00:09:57,400 --> 00:10:05,400
then we need to look at how can we spot or at least identify people who are trying to contribute and actually bring them in and have a discussion with them.

108
00:10:05,400 --> 00:10:09,400
Because I don't know if anyone else remembers the feeling when they get their PR merged the first time.

109
00:10:09,400 --> 00:10:19,400
It's just especially see Python like it's yeah, it's a you know, it's a pretty high bar to get something into see Python.

110
00:10:19,400 --> 00:10:22,400
And there are people doing this every day from all over the world.

111
00:10:22,400 --> 00:10:26,400
So I think we definitely need to look at how we can bring more of them on board.

112
00:10:26,400 --> 00:10:39,400
I do. I do feel that living in Asia previously that a lot of people or developers in Asia feel that they're not capable.

113
00:10:39,400 --> 00:10:48,400
They're not good enough. Is there a way to actually make them reassure that they can actually contribute and they actually good enough?

114
00:10:48,400 --> 00:10:49,400
Anyone of you can.

115
00:10:49,400 --> 00:10:56,400
I think mentoring is a has been demonstrated to be really effective with bringing on core developers.

116
00:10:56,400 --> 00:11:08,400
So existing core developers mentoring people and there have definitely been cases of that with new core developers from from Africa and also from Asia and people existing core developers mentoring them.

117
00:11:08,400 --> 00:11:12,400
I think that's been really effective in terms of the resources as well.

118
00:11:12,400 --> 00:11:14,400
It's really important.

119
00:11:15,400 --> 00:11:21,400
So, so what do you think how we can actually reach out to these people?

120
00:11:21,400 --> 00:11:33,400
So look, I think a big problem is just sort of the perception of software in general and Python and open source software in particular that for many people, they're like, OK, I have software.

121
00:11:33,400 --> 00:11:37,400
And when they see open source, they don't think oh, community supported and written.

122
00:11:37,400 --> 00:11:41,400
They think free, right? I could download it. I don't need to pay for this thing.

123
00:11:41,400 --> 00:11:48,400
Certainly a lot of companies say that and think that and the notion of oh, there's a problem with this or there's something that could be better.

124
00:11:48,400 --> 00:11:54,400
I can change it. I can be part of that improvement that doesn't occur to most people and then take it even a step further.

125
00:11:54,400 --> 00:12:01,400
The notion that there's an organization that's charter is to help people improve the language based on their needs.

126
00:12:01,400 --> 00:12:03,400
That's like the furthest thing from their minds.

127
00:12:03,400 --> 00:12:09,400
So the first thing I think we have to do is do a better job of telling these people the PSF exists, the community exists.

128
00:12:09,400 --> 00:12:12,400
It's not just a word, oh, the Python community, it's all the people use it.

129
00:12:12,400 --> 00:12:17,400
There is an actual community and you can join it and you can be active and you can influence its direction.

130
00:12:17,400 --> 00:12:23,400
And once people have that sense of oh, we can influence it, then we can start to talk to them about the different ways to do it.

131
00:12:23,400 --> 00:12:28,400
Code, documentation, translation, teaching, the works.

